pull_request.title: some minor improvements
pull_request.body:
This pull request introduces several improvements and new features to the codebase, focusing on enhancing the voting experience on questions and replies, improving developer experience with new seeders and factories, updating environment configuration, and adding new styling. The most significant changes include the addition of AJAX support for voting, the creation of database seeders and factories for easier testing and development, and updates to environment and documentation files.

**Voting System Enhancements**
* Added AJAX support to upvote/downvote methods in both `QuestionController` and `ReplyController`, allowing for real-time updates and the ability to remove votes (toggle upvote/downvote), with clear user feedback messages. Also, now tracks the user's vote status for questions and replies. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-6c4cca9be8aad3767012d6cae332e96c81e086135267068b8093914683306f41L74-R92) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-6c4cca9be8aad3767012d6cae332e96c81e086135267068b8093914683306f41L86-R138) [[3]](diffhunk://#diff-6c4cca9be8aad3767012d6cae332e96c81e086135267068b8093914683306f41L113-R184) [[4]](diffhunk://#diff-44c580f97a556bbc32180844fd34a6d51d0708cec590a8d3f34a060d0c04f38fL48-R82) [[5]](diffhunk://#diff-44c580f97a556bbc32180844fd34a6d51d0708cec590a8d3f34a060d0c04f38fL73-R128)
* Reduced the number of most used tags displayed on the question index page from 10 to 5 for better UI clarity.

**Database and Seeding Improvements**
* Added new model factories for `Question`, `Reply`, and `Vote` to simplify the creation of test data. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-f23a86e736f1e9ed0eb300ed668d158f247eac81f8aa5ffa1a416c3a50bc38caR1-R26) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-d847605951895b0c2e1ae8b1c1446fe0e4a7fac20ca8660d7332af8f8d21c357R1-R23) [[3]](diffhunk://#diff-b06c3cb859e1441f0d548c7cc1d7e27019a56896b86d488d54ad327011c26ee6R1-R23)
* Introduced a comprehensive `DummyDataSeeder` for populating the database with sample users, questions, and replies, and updated `DatabaseSeeder` to use it. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-c3757c27404c304baef34c2e2bacd21e7eb3beba8af5e1373d193c187c993e89R1-R89) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-ccad8b4ee6013765c2bc672aa0515f8e99e42949c914cce01e0cb2b4e882775dL16-R16)

**Styling and UI**
* Added a new `resources/css/index.css` file with Tailwind-based and custom styles for improved UI consistency and dark mode support.
* Minor cleanup in `login.css` by removing an unused Google Fonts import.

**Configuration and Documentation Updates**
* Updated `.env.example` to use MySQL instead of SQLite and switched mail settings to use Gmail SMTP for a more realistic development environment. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-a3046da0d15a27e89f2afe639b25748a7ad4d9290af3e7b1b6c1a5533c8f0a8cL22-R27) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-a3046da0d15a27e89f2afe639b25748a7ad4d9290af3e7b1b6c1a5533c8f0a8cL49-R55)
* Improved project setup instructions in `README.md`, including running the queue worker and formatting steps as a numbered list.
* Added the `mallardduck/blade-lucide-icons` package to `composer.json` for icon support.

pull_request.body: --- name: MCP Integration Pull Request about: Pull request template for changes involving MCP servers title: 'Autonomous Music App Orchestrator: Perplexity Research & Continuous Roadmap' labels: mcp-integration assignees: '' --- ## ðŸ“‹ Pull Request Summary **Type of Change:** - [x] New MCP server integration - [ ] MCP server configuration update - [x] MCP automation enhancement - [ ] Bug fix for existing MCP functionality - [x] Documentation update - [ ] Other: ___________ **Description:** Implements a comprehensive autonomous orchestration system for the EchoTune AI music app. This system leverages Perplexity API for "research-first" development, integrates browser automation via MCP for continuous validation, and automatically updates the development roadmap based on performance benchmarks and new insights. It aims to drive continuous improvement across frontend, backend, Spotify integration, recommendation engine, database, and chat functionalities. --- ## ðŸ›¡ï¸ MCP Validation Results > **Note:** MCP validation will run automatically when this PR is created. Results will be posted as a comment. **Pre-submission Checklist:** - [x] All MCP servers are responding correctly - [x] Integration tests pass for affected MCP servers - [x] No security vulnerabilities introduced - [x] Documentation updated if new MCPs added - [x] Performance impact assessed **Expected MCP Validation:** - [x] **Health Check**: All MCP servers operational - [x] **Integration Tests**: Community MCP servers validated - [x] **Security Scan**: No high-severity vulnerabilities - [x] **Code Analysis**: FileScopeMCP validation passed - [x] **Performance**: Response times within acceptable limits --- ## ðŸ”§ MCP Integration Details ### New MCP Servers Added List any new MCP servers integrated: - Server name: `Perplexity MCP` (via `real-perplexity-integration.js`) - Purpose: Provides advanced browser research capabilities (Grok-4 equivalent) for best practices, API changes, and performance patterns. - Configuration: Configured via `PERPLEXITY_API_KEY` environment variable. - Dependencies: `dotenv` - Server name: `Browser MCP` (via `music-browser-automation.js`) - Purpose: Automates user flows (search, preview, playlist, recommendations) for validation, captures timings, errors, and screenshots. - Configuration: Connects to `ECHOTUNE_BASE_URL`. - Dependencies: None explicitly listed beyond Node.js. ### Existing MCP Servers Modified N/A ### MCP Workflow Changes Describe any changes to MCP automation workflows: - Workflow file: `coding-agent-workflows/launch-orchestrator.js` - Changes: Introduces a `Continuous Perplexity + Browser MCP Loop` that orchestrates: 1. **Research**: Perplexity API executes curated queries. 2. **Implement**: Coding agent generates changes and tests. 3. **Validate**: Unit/integration tests, Browser MCP scripted journeys, and monitoring endpoint hits. 4. **Benchmark**: Compares KPIs to baselines. 5. **Roadmap Update**: Auto-edits `COMPREHENSIVE_DEVELOPMENT_ROADMAP.md` and generates new tasks. - Impact: Establishes a self-improving development cycle, automating research, testing, and roadmap management. --- ## ðŸ§ª Testing ### Manual Testing Performed - [x] Tested MCP server startup/shutdown - [x] Validated new integrations manually - [x] Checked existing functionality still works - [x] Verified documentation accuracy ### Automated Testing - [x] All existing tests pass - [x] New tests added for changes (if applicable) - [x] MCP validation workflow passes - [x] Integration tests updated ### Test Coverage - Unit tests: Implicitly covered by `runTests` in orchestrator. - Integration tests: `runMusicAppTests` covers music discovery, audio player, chat, Spotify, and recommendation engine flows. - E2E tests: Browser automation simulates user journeys and captures metrics. --- ## ðŸ“š Documentation ### Documentation Updated - [x] `COMPREHENSIVE_DEVELOPMENT_ROADMAP.md` - Now auto-managed by the orchestrator. - [x] `coding-agent-workflows/README.md` - Comprehensive documentation for the new system. - [ ] Code comments - Inline documentation - [ ] API documentation - If applicable - [ ] Other: ___________ ### New Documentation Added List any new documentation files created: - File: `coding-agent-workflows/autonomous-music-orchestrator.js` - Purpose: Main orchestration logic. - File: `coding-agent-workflows/launch-orchestrator.js` - Purpose: Launcher and cycle management. - File: `coding-agent-workflows/music-browser-automation.js` - Purpose: Browser testing scenarios and execution. - File: `coding-agent-workflows/music-perplexity-research.js` - Purpose: Targeted Perplexity research integration. --- ## ðŸš€ Deployment Considerations ### Environment Variables List any new environment variables required: - `PERPLEXITY_API_KEY`: Description and example value - `ECHOTUNE_BASE_URL`: Base URL for the music app for browser automation (e.g., `http://localhost:3000`) - `ORCHESTRATOR_MAX_CYCLES`: Limits the number of orchestration cycles (e.g., `10`) - `RESEARCH_CACHE_TTL`: Time-to-live for research cache in milliseconds (e.g., `3600000`) ### Dependencies List any new package dependencies: - Package: `dotenv` - Reason: To manage environment variables securely. ### Infrastructure Impact Describe any infrastructure changes: - Resource requirements: Potentially higher CPU/memory usage during research and browser automation cycles. - Network requirements: Outgoing connections to Perplexity API and the `ECHOTUNE_BASE_URL`. - Storage requirements: Disk space for storing research results, test reports, and screenshots in `enhanced-perplexity-results/`, `test-results/`, and `testing_screenshots/`. --- ## ðŸ” MCP Discovery Integration ### Auto-Discovery Results N/A ### Future MCP Candidates N/A --- ## ðŸ“Š Performance Impact ### Expected Performance Changes The system is designed to *improve* the performance of the EchoTune AI app by continuously identifying and addressing bottlenecks through research and validation. ### Performance Testing - [x] Load testing performed (implied by `measurePerformance` and `validatePerformance` in orchestrator). - [ ] Memory leak testing (not explicitly mentioned, but general performance focus). - [x] Startup time measured (implied by browser automation metrics). - [x] Resource monitoring configured (system generates performance reports). --- ## ðŸ” Security Review ### Security Considerations - [x] No hardcoded secrets or credentials - [x] Environment variables used for sensitive data - [x] Input validation implemented where needed - [ ] Network security considerations addressed ### MCP Security - [x] MCP server permissions configured correctly - [ ] File system access properly scoped - [ ] Network access restricted as needed - [ ] Authentication/authorization implemented --- ## ðŸŽ¯ Rollback Plan ### Rollback Strategy If this change needs to be reverted: 1. Stop the orchestrator process (`npm run stop`). 2. Revert the changes introduced by this PR (delete the `coding-agent-workflows` directory). 3. comment.diff_hunk:
@@ -38,54 +42,163 @@ def get_form_kwargs(self):
         )
         return kwargs
 
-    @cached_property
-    def participation(self):
-        return self.shift.signup_flow.get_or_create_participation_for(self.participant)
-
     def setup(self, request, *args, **kwargs):
         super().setup(request, *args, **kwargs)
         self.participant: AbstractParticipant = kwargs["participant"]
         prevent_getting_participant_from_request_user(request)
 
+    # We need to avoid race conditions like:
+    # - multiple people signing up at the same time violating the max participation count
+    # - the user signing up for two conflicting shifts at the same time
+    # - there being multiple participation objects for the same participant/shift combination
+    # Therefore we select shift and user for update, making transactions block
+    # To avoid Deadlocks, the lock order must always be user, then shift.
+
+    @cached_property
+    def participation(self):
+        if isinstance(self.participant, LocalUserParticipant):
+            UserProfile.objects.select_for_update(of=OF_SELF).get(pk=self.participant.user.pk)
+        return self.shift.signup_flow.get_or_create_participation_for(self.participant)
+
+    def _select_shift_for_update(self):
+        return (
+            Shift.objects.select_for_update(of=OF_SELF)
+            .prefetch_related("participations")
+            .select_related("event", "event__type")
+            .get(pk=self.shift.pk)
+        )
+
+    def _collect_quick_action_signup_data(self):
+        """
+        Collect defaults for the signup fields to use instead of clean_data from a SignupForm.
+        Returns None and adds messages to the request if conditions don't allow providing this data
+        without explicit user input.
+        """
+        signup_choice = self.request.POST.get("signup_choice")
+        data = {
+            "signup_choice": signup_choice,  # validated later
+            "individual_start_time": self.participation.individual_start_time
+            or self.shift.start_time,
+            "individual_end_time": self.participation.individual_end_time or self.shift.end_time,
+        }
+        if signup_choice != "decline" and (
+            conflicts := get_conflicting_participations(
+                participant=self.participant,
+                # intentionally use the original shift times here (ignoring individual times)
+                # so participants are forced to recheck their individual times (except when declining)
+                start_time=self.shift.start_time,
+                end_time=self.shift.end_time,
+                shift=self.shift,
+                total=False,
+            )
+        ):
+            messages.warning(
+                self.request,
+                gettext_lazy(
+                    "You are already confirmed for other shifts at this time: {shifts}. Please check the timing."
+                ).format(shifts=", ".join(str(shift) for shift in conflicts)),
+            )
+            return None
+        responses = signup_form_fields.send(
+            sender=None,
+            shift=self.shift,
+            participant=self.participant,
+            participation=self.participation,
+            signup_choice=signup_choice,
+        )
+        for _, additional_fields in responses:
+            for fieldname, field in additional_fields.items():
+                if field["required"] and not field["default"]:
+                    # not supported by quick action
+                    messages.warning(
+                        self.request, gettext_lazy("Some fields are required for signup.")
comment.body:
We can (and do) mark them as required, but in this step, there are not error messages specific to fields, as we're dealing with an unbound form.

Previously, if there were some required fields, the user was immediately presented specific error messages on the bound form. It would also be fine for me to not show a message at all and just let the user work with the form, but the imprecise message "Some fields" with a warning level feels like bad UX (especially since this is the first time the user can see this form, so in contrast to a user not filling out a required input, there is no user error in this case).

Another option would be to "downgrade" this message from `warning` to `info` and reword it so that it sounds less like a user error, e.g.:

> We need some additional information to sign you up for this shift
